[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    564[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    565[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    566[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few cross-cutting design points specific to the care-coordination assistant.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    567[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    568[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Integration breadth as architectural primitive.** The integration layer is the single most important component. Each integrated system (scheduling, referral management, EHR, prior-authorization tracking, pharmacy, home-health tracking, financial-assistance tracking) has its own ownership, failure modes, and operational discipline. The integration layer is built and maintained by the institutional integration team in partnership with operations, with FHIR-native sourcing where available and direct integrations where FHIR is not yet in place.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    569[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    570[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-pathway-as-code with care-management-leadership ownership.** Each care pathway is owned by the appropriate clinical-and-operational leadership (oncology service-line leadership for oncology pathways, transplant program leadership for transplant pathways, heart failure clinic leadership for advanced HF pathway, etc.), reviewed before adoption, reviewed annually, and re-reviewed when material updates are made.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    571[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    572[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-system reconciliation as core capability.** The assistant compares operational state across multiple systems, identifies discrepancies, and surfaces them. The reconciliation logic is structured, owned by the integration team, and audited.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    573[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    574[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Action-confirmation discipline.** High-stakes actions (sending messages on the patient's behalf, scheduling appointments, refilling prescriptions, submitting prior-auth-related communications) require explicit patient confirmation. The action-confirmation pattern is an architectural primitive; bypassing it for "user convenience" is a documented failure mode that has produced patient-facing harm in other deployments.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    575[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    576[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-pathway-deviation severity classification.** Deviations are classified per care pathway with severity tiers: informational, soft-flag, care-team-alert, urgent-clinical-review. The classifications are reviewed by clinical leadership.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    577[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    578[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-team and care-coordinator workforce integration.** The assistant escalates appropriately to the institution's existing care-management workforce or, where that workforce does not exist, directly to the patient's care team. The institutional workforce architecture determines the assistant's escalation routing, not the other way around.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    579[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    580[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Per-cohort monitoring is non-negotiable.** Coordination-coverage rate, coordination-completion rate, engagement rate, attrition rate, action-confirmation rate, care-team alert volume, and patient satisfaction vary by language, channel, care pathway, age cohort, sex, social-determinant flags, and digital-fluency proxies. Per-cohort dashboards reviewed by clinical leadership, operations, compliance, and patient-experience teams.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    581[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    582[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Disaster-recovery topology.** When integrated operational systems are unreachable, the assistant degrades gracefully. The minimum behavior is "I can't pull that data right now; for anything urgent please contact your care team at [number]." Per-source failover behavior is documented and tested.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    583[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    584[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
